# Dealing with Null Values

We can see there are a lot of Null values in our dataset and we will have to deal with null values of each column differently 

## Club

Simply Replace the players without any club as "Free Agents"

## *Free Agents*  : 

In professional association football, a free agent is either a player that has been released by a professional association football club and now is no longer affiliated with any league, or a player whose contract with his or her current club has expired and is thus free to join any other club under the terms of the Bosman ruling.


```python
# Null values of Club column

df['Club'].fillna("Free Agents", inplace = True)
```

## General Position


```python
df['Position'].unique()
```




    array(['RF', 'ST', 'LW', 'GK', 'RCM', 'LF', 'RS', 'RCB', 'LCM', 'CB',
           'LDM', 'CAM', 'CDM', 'LS', 'LCB', 'RM', 'LAM', 'LM', 'LB', 'RDM',
           'RW', 'CM', 'RB', 'RAM', 'CF', 'RWB', 'LWB', nan], dtype=object)




```python
def gen_pos(val):
    if val =='GK':
        return 'Goalkeeper'
    elif val == 'LCB' or val == 'CB' or val == 'RCB' or val == 'LB' or val == 'RB' or val=='LWB' or val=='RWB':
        return 'Defender'
    elif val =='CDM' or val =='LDM' or val =='RDM':
        return 'Defensive Midfielder'
    elif val=='LCM' or val=='RCM' or val=='CM' or val=='CAM' or val=='LAM'or val=='RAM' or val=='LM' or val=='RM':
        return 'Midfielder'
    elif val=='CF' or val=='ST' or val=='LW' or val=='RW' or val=='LS' or val =='RS' or val=='LF' or val=='RF':
        return 'Forward'
    
df['General Position'] = df['Position'].apply(gen_pos)
```

```python
def convert_value(val):
    if val == '€0':
        return 0
    
    multiplier = val[-1] 
    val = val[1:-1]

    val = float(val)
    
    if multiplier == 'M':
        val = val * 1000000
    elif multiplier == 'K':
        val = val * 1000
    else:
        val = val
    return val
    
df['Wage'] = df['Wage'].apply(convert_value) 
```

## Skill Columns : Crossing, Finishing, Heading Accuracy etc etc

Skill Columns such as Crossing, Finishing, Heading Accuracy will require a different way of dealing with null values.

Instead of just looking at the Overall of the players, it is important to also look at the position in which these players play since these attributes are related to the position as well.

For e.g. Defenders are likely to have a higher rating for Tackling, Marking etc while Strikers are more likely to have a higher rating for Finishing, Composure and Positioning


```python
# Filling the NaNs in the Position column with 'No position' in order to facilitate group by in the next step

df['Position'].fillna('No Position', inplace=True)
```


```python
# Grouping the Skill Columns by Overall and then Position

groupby_overall_positon = pd.DataFrame(df[['Crossing', 'Finishing',
       'HeadingAccuracy', 'ShortPassing', 'Volleys', 'Dribbling', 'Curve',
       'FKAccuracy', 'LongPassing', 'BallControl', 'Acceleration',
       'SprintSpeed', 'Agility', 'Reactions', 'Balance', 'ShotPower',
       'Jumping', 'Stamina', 'Strength', 'LongShots', 'Aggression',

       'Marking', 'StandingTackle', 'SlidingTackle', 'GKDiving', 'GKHandling',
       'GKKicking', 'GKPositioning', 'GKReflexes','Overall', 'Position']].groupby(['Overall', 'Position']).mean().round())
```

I will try to categorise all the attributes into 4 major categories : 
    
<ul>
   
<li> Defensive Attributes </li>

    
<li> Midfield Attributes </li>

    
<li> Striker Attributes </li>

    
<li> GoalKeeper Attributes </li>

</ul>


The idea is to take various attributes that would make up these categories and then determine the average of these attributes to get a final Defensive Score, Midfield Score, Attacking Score and Goal Keeping score.


Based on the score which will be maximum, the player is then assigned a particular position. 

For e.g. if the Defensive score of the player is highest among all then they will be assigned a position : 'CB'

For Defensive Score, the attributes chosen are:
    
<ul>
   
<li> Marking </li>

    
<li> Standing Tackle </li>

    
<li> Sliding Tackle </li>

    
<li> Heading Accuracy </li>
    

<li> Interceptions </li>

</ul>    

For Midfield Score, the attributes chosen are:
    
<ul>
   
<li> Short Passing </li>

    
<li> Long Passing </li>

    
<li> Dribbling </li>

    
<li> Curve </li>
    

<li> Ball Control </li>

    
<li> Crossing </li>


<li> Vision </li>
    
    
</ul>    

For Striker Score, the attributes chosen are:
    
<ul>
   
<li> Volleys </li>

    
<li> Finishing </li>

    
<li> Positioning </li>

    
<li> Compure </li>    
    
</ul>    

For Goalkeeper Score, the attributes chosen are:
    
<ul>
   
<li> GKDiving </li>

    
<li> GKReflexes </li>

    
<li> GKPositioning </li>

    
<li> GKKicking </li>
    

<li> GKHandling </li>

</ul>    

#### The Idea is to replicate something similar with the existing database:-

Hence, I will further categorise all the attributes into these many categories

![SOFIFAPNG.PNG](attachment:SOFIFAPNG.PNG)


```python
# Calculating average position wise Attributes to determine the position of the player

df['defensive_score'] = (df['Marking'] + df['StandingTackle'] + df['SlidingTackle'] + df['HeadingAccuracy'] + df['Interceptions'])/5

df['midfield_score'] = (df['ShortPassing'] + df['Dribbling'] + df['Curve'] + df['LongPassing'] + df['BallControl'] + df['Crossing'] + df['Vision'])/7

df['striker_score'] = (df['Volleys'] + df['Finishing'] + df['Positioning'] + df['Composure']) / 4

df['goalkeeper_score']= (df['GKDiving'] + df['GKHandling'] + df['GKKicking'] + df['GKPositioning'] + df['GKReflexes']) / 5


# Referenced from Sofifa : https://sofifa.com/

df['Movement_Attributes'] = (df['Acceleration'] + df['SprintSpeed'] + df['Reactions'] + df['Balance'] + df['Agility']) / 5

df['Power_Attributes'] = (df['Strength'] + df['Jumping'] + df['ShotPower'] + df['Stamina'] + df['LongShots']) / 5

df['Mentality_Attributes'] = (df['Aggression'] + df['Interceptions'] + df['Vision'] + df['Positioning'] + df['Penalties'] + df['Composure']) / 6

df['Skill_Attributes'] =  (df['Dribbling'] + df['Curve'] + df['FKAccuracy'] + df['LongPassing'] + df['BallControl']) / 5

```


```python
# Rounding the above calculated new columns

df['defensive_score'] = df['defensive_score'].round()
df['midfield_score'] = df['midfield_score'].round()
df['striker_score'] = df['striker_score'].round()
df['Skill_Attributes'] = df['Skill_Attributes'].round()
df['Movement_Attributes'] = df['Movement_Attributes'].round()
df['Mentality_Attributes'] = df['Mentality_Attributes'].round()
df['Power_Attributes'] = df['Power_Attributes'].round()
df['goalkeeper_score'] = df['goalkeeper_score'].round()
```

```python
# Defining a function that would return the position based on the 4 scores defined

def define_position(row):
    max_attr = max(row['defensive_score'], row['midfield_score'], row['striker_score'], row['goalkeeper_score'])
    if max_attr == row['goalkeeper_score']:
        return 'GK'
    elif max_attr == row['defensive_score']:
        return 'CB'
    elif max_attr == row['midfield_score']:
        return 'CM'
    elif max_attr == row['striker_score']:
        return 'CF'    
```


```python
# Applying the function

df['Position'] = df.apply(lambda row: define_position(row) if row['Position']=='No Position' else row['Position'], axis = 1)
```

```python
# Grouping the Skill Moves based on the position
```

## Age Bracket


```python
def age_bracket(val):
    
    if val < 18:
        return "Under 17"
    elif val >=18 and val <22:
        return "18-21"
    elif val >=22 and val <27:
        return "22-26"
    elif val >=27 and val <32:
        return "27-31"
    elif val >=32 and val <36:
        return "32-35"    
    else:
        return "36 +"
    
df['Age Bracket'] = df['Age'].apply(age_bracket)
```

The logical thing to replace Height would be to use Weight but we can see that for all the NaN entries, both Height and Weight are not available 

Hence, the next idea is to replace the Height and using the Nationality and the Position in which the players play



But we can see that the Height is in Feet, hence it is important to clean that first in order to apply Group By later


```python
def clean_height(x):
    l=[]
    s=1
    if isinstance(x,str):
        l=x.split("'")
        i=int(l[0])
        j=int(l[1])
        s=((i*12)+j)/12
    return(s)


df['Height'] = df['Height'].apply(clean_height)
```

It is diffcult to apply groupby directly since Height is a continuous value.

The logical thing would be to categorize Height and then fill the Null values in weight column by using average of each Height Category


```python
# creating spearate height column "height_category" to categorize the height of the players

def height_category(val):
    if val >= 5 and val < 5.3:
        return "Category 1"
    elif val >= 5.3 and val < 5.7:
        return "Category 2"    
    elif val >= 5.7 and val < 6:
        return "Category 3"
    elif val >= 6 and val < 6.3:
        return "Category 4"    
    elif val >= 6.3 and val < 6.7:
        return "Category 5"
    else:
        return "Category 6"
    
df['height_category'] = df['Height'].apply(height_category)    
```

## Release Clause

#### *Release Clause* :

It is a clause in a player’s contract that, subject to qualifying conditions (i.e. a particular transfer window or non-participation in the Champions League), automatically requires a club to accept an offer of a pre-determined contractual amount expressly set out in the contract from the offering club.  If the minimum amount stipulated in the contract is triggered by a the purchasing club, the player will be entitled to speak to that club.

The players who have NaN in their Release Clause column are players who simply don't have a release clause and have to be bought only through Negotitation with the parent club

I will simply replace NaN with "No Release Clause"


```python
# Filling out the NaN values

df['Release Clause'].fillna("No Release Clause", inplace = True)
```

```python
def PosConverter(val):
    if type(val) == str:
        s1 = val[0:2]
        s2 = val[-1]
        val = int(s1) + int(s2)
        return val
    else:
        return val

for col in pos_columns:
    df[col] = df[col].apply(PosConverter)
```

```python
df_wo = df.loc[filter]
```

```python
def pie_chart(df, field):

    new_df = df[field].value_counts().to_frame()
    total = df[field].value_counts().sum()
    new_df['Percentage'] = new_df[field] / total * 100

    labels = new_df.index.to_list()
    values = new_df['Percentage'].to_list()

    fig = px.pie(new_df, values= new_df['Percentage'], names=labels, title='Percentage of players by ' + field)
    fig.update_layout(paper_bgcolor='#2A2C2D', title_font_color='white', font_color ='white',legend_bordercolor='white',legend_borderwidth=3.5)
    fig.show()
```

## Age v/s Overall


```python
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
ax = plt.axes()
ticks = [13,16,19,22,25,28,31,34,37,40,43,46,49,52,55]
ax.set_xticks(ticks) 
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="Age", y="Overall");
```




    <matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2925637a5c8>




![png](FIFA_19_files/FIFA_19_215_1.png)


We can clearly that most players peak around 27-29 years and dip considerably afterwards. In fact in football, ages 26-29 are regarded as player's prime where they expect them to be at their best game 


```python
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
ax = plt.axes()
ticks = [13,16,19,22,25,28,31,34,37,40,43,46,49,52,55]
ax.set_xticks(ticks) 
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="Age", y="Overall", hue='General Position');
```




    <matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x292564130c8>




![png](FIFA_19_files/FIFA_19_217_1.png)


The graph clearly shows that the position in which the players play also matters in terms of when their overall will 'Dip'.

Goalkeepers tend to play at at higher level (higher overall rating) for a longer time (34 years) than any other players. They are followed by defenders who tend to dip after 32 years of age

Forwards see a steep drop in their rating after hitting 29

```python
def wage_budget(val):
    if val >= 4000000:
        return 'Greater than 4M'
    elif val >= 3000000 and val < 4000000:
        return '3-4 M'
    elif val >= 2000000 and val < 3000000:
        return '2-3 M'
    elif val >= 1000000 and val < 2000000:
        return '1-2 M'
    else:
        return 'Less than 1 M'
    
df_wage_budget['Bracket'] = df_wage_budget['Wage'].apply(wage_budget)
```

```python
df_new = df_new.loc[:,~df_new.columns.duplicated()]
```


```python
def wage_budget_overall(val):
    if val >= 60000:
        return 'Greater than 60k'
    elif val >= 40000 and val < 60000 :
        return '40k - 60k'
    elif val >= 20000 and val < 40000:
        return '20k - 40k'
    elif val >= 10000 and val < 20000:
        return '10k - 20k'
    else:
        return 'Less than 10k'
    
df_new['Bracket'] = df_new['Wage / Overall'].apply(wage_budget_overall)
```

Teams like Dortmund who make the list of highest rated teams by average do not make it to the list of ' Wage/ Overall'.

This tells that Dortmund is very good at keeping their wage budget low while buying/having strong players

## 5. (B) Average rating of each team with the best line up


```python
def best_fit_helper_1(df,defence, mid, fwd):
    
    result =  pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Club', 'Name', 'Overall'])
    res_1 = {}
    res_2 = {}
    positions = defence + mid + fwd
    for pos in positions:
        temp = df[['Name', 'Overall','Club', pos]].sort_values(pos, ascending = False).head(10)
        
        for index, row in temp.iterrows():
            if row['Name'] in res_2 :
                continue
            else:
                res_2[row['Name']] = 1
                res_1[pos] = [row['Name'], row['Overall']] 
                result = result.append({'Club' : row['Club'],'Position': pos,'Name' : row['Name'], 'Overall' : row['Overall'],}, ignore_index=True)
                break
                
        if len(positions) == len(res_1):
            return result
```


```python
main_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Club', 'Average Overall'])
for club in df['Club'].unique():

    main_df = main_df.append({'Club' : club, 'Average Overall': temp_res['Overall'].mean().round()}, ignore_index=True)
```

# Dream Team


```python
def best_fit_helper(defence, mid, fwd):
    
    result = {}
    res_2 = {}
    positions = defence + mid + fwd
    for pos in positions:
        temp = df[['Name', 'Overall', pos]].sort_values(pos, ascending = False).head(10)
        
        for index, row in temp.iterrows():
            if row['Name'] in res_2 :
                continue
            else:
                res_2[row['Name']] = 1
                result[pos] = [row['Name'], row['Overall']] 
                break
                
        if len(positions) == len(result):
            return result
```
